# Observability Rules

## Applicability

Apply this rule when changing:

- tracing API or runtime behavior
- span creation, naming, relationships, links, events, or attributes
- context propagation or MDC
- sampling or force-sampling
- scrubbing or PII handling
- Micrometer/OTel metrics
- structured logging
- health, readiness, startup diagnostics, or runtime diagnostics
- exporters, processors, collectors, queues, retries, or drops
- servlet, WebFlux, Kafka, database, async, or scheduled instrumentation

Before adding telemetry, identify the concrete operational question it answers.

Do not instrument code merely because telemetry can be added.

## Signal Ownership

Every signal must have one owner.

- Traces belong to tracing API/core and OTel integration.
- Platform metrics belong to the approved telemetry/runtime module.
- Structured logging follows platform logging conventions.
- Health and readiness belong to Spring Boot Actuator/infrastructure integration.
- Runtime diagnostics belong to bounded read-only diagnostics surfaces.

Do not duplicate signals already emitted by the Java agent, OTel SDK, Micrometer, Spring Boot, or client libraries.

## Required Decision Record

For every new or changed signal, define:

```text
Operational question:
Signal type:
Owner module:
Name:
Dimensions/attributes:
Cardinality budget:
Sensitive-data assessment:
Disabled/no-op behavior:
Failure/degradation behavior:
Test evidence:
```

A signal without a consumer or operator use case is observability noise.

## Tracing

Use OpenTelemetry and W3C Trace Context.

Do not:

- invent custom trace formats
- reimplement W3C parsing when the approved OTel implementation is available
- expose OTel SDK implementation types through application-facing API
- create manual spans that duplicate auto-instrumentation
- use tracing metadata for authentication or authorization
- log full malformed propagation headers

Manual spans require a demonstrated semantic gap.

## Span Naming

Span names must be:

- stable
- low cardinality
- based on operation or normalized route
- free of raw identifiers and payload values

Preferred:

```text
payment.process
GET /orders/{id}
kafka.consume
```

Forbidden:

```text
payment.user-123
GET /orders/98765
consume.customer@example.com
```

Do not include trace IDs, span IDs, request IDs, user/account IDs, query strings, timestamps, or exception messages in span names.

## Span Design

Create spans only for meaningful operations or boundaries.

Avoid:

- one span per trivial method
- one span per loop item without a volume budget
- excessive nesting
- duplicate transport spans
- duplicate exception events

Where applicable, verify:

- span count
- name
- parent/root/link relationship
- trace continuity
- attributes
- status and events
- resource identity
- sampling outcome
- absence of duplicates

## Span Lifecycle

Spans and scopes must be closed deterministically.

Requirements:

- start exactly once
- end exactly once
- restore previous context
- preserve lifecycle semantics in no-op mode
- avoid leaks on exception, cancellation, or retry
- document reuse/thread-safety for builders and handles

Do not rely on garbage collection or finalizers.

## Attributes and Events

Attributes and event data must be:

- operationally useful
- bounded
- type-safe
- stable
- reviewed for cardinality and privacy

Do not:

- use user input as an attribute key
- attach raw payloads
- attach credentials, cookies, tokens, or authorization headers
- attach unbounded maps or collections
- copy arbitrary baggage into attributes
- attach full SQL or message payloads
- blindly record exception messages

Use approved semantic conventions and platform-owned namespaces.

## Cardinality

Every metric tag and aggregatable attribute needs a bounded value set or explicit budget.

Generally forbidden as metric labels:

- trace ID
- span ID
- request ID
- user/account ID
- raw route/path
- endpoint URL
- exception message
- baggage value
- arbitrary rule/configuration value

If a value can grow without a deployment, treat it as high cardinality.

## Metrics

Use Micrometer unless a lower-level OTel metric path is explicitly required.

Metrics must be:

- stable
- low cardinality
- bounded
- aggregatable
- operationally useful
- owned by one module

Before adding a metric, inspect existing OTel, agent, Spring Boot, Micrometer, and client-library metrics.

Do not add a duplicate metric because an internal counter is available.

Use:

- counters for monotonic events
- gauges for stable current state with a clear owner
- timers/histograms only for a concrete latency question

Do not use dynamic metric names.

## Structured Logging

Use parameterized and structured logging.

Logs must:

- identify the capability
- include bounded machine-readable status/reason fields where useful
- preserve root cause safely
- be actionable
- avoid repeated floods

Never log:

- secrets
- credentials
- tokens
- authorization headers
- cookies
- raw control payloads
- raw baggage
- full malformed trace headers
- raw PII
- exporter credentials
- full environment/configuration dumps

Do not emit one INFO log per span or sampling decision.

## Logging Levels

Use:

- `ERROR` for unsafe or unrecoverable platform failures
- `WARN` for bounded degraded states, rejected unsafe configuration, or operator action
- `INFO` for concise lifecycle/mode summaries
- `DEBUG`/`TRACE` for bounded troubleshooting

Do not require DEBUG logs to understand a critical production failure.

Warning deduplication must be bounded, thread-safe, and test-isolated.

## Correlation and Context

MDC is a logging integration, not the source of truth.

Use validated/current trace context to populate correlation fields.

Requirements:

- restore previous MDC values
- clean up on success, error, cancellation, and retry
- do not assume ThreadLocal propagation in Reactor
- do not mutate trace context from MDC
- keep correlation fields small and stable
- do not use request/correlation IDs as metric labels

Test no cross-request or cross-subscription leakage.

## Reactive and Async Flows

Do not:

- block Reactor event-loop threads
- rely on plain ThreadLocal propagation
- create hidden subscriptions
- add unbounded retries
- duplicate spans across retries/subscriptions
- perform synchronous export on reactive/request threads

Test:

- thread hops
- context visibility
- context restoration
- cancellation
- error path
- retry behavior
- MDC cleanup
- outbound propagation
- duplicate instrumentation

## Propagation and Baggage

Incoming propagation data is untrusted.

Use the approved OTel propagators.

Do not:

- trust trace context for authorization
- copy arbitrary baggage into logs or spans
- propagate secrets or raw PII
- accept unbounded baggage
- echo raw invalid request IDs or headers

Baggage requires an allowlist and size limits.

## Sampling

Sampling must be deterministic and explainable.

Require:

- validated ratios
- explicit route precedence
- normalized route templates
- deterministic tests using `0.0` or `1.0` where appropriate
- readable applied state
- last-known-good preservation after rejected mutation
- no conflict between platform and OTel sampler settings

Force sampling must not bypass:

- scrubbing
- export kill switches
- runtime mutation policy
- security controls

## Scrubbing and PII

Scrubbing is a production safety control.

State its exact scope.

A span-attribute processor does not automatically protect:

- events
- links
- baggage
- resources
- logs
- metrics

Require:

- deterministic rules
- visibility of active/skipped rules
- safe rule fingerprint
- explicit critical failure behavior
- no raw sensitive values in diagnostics
- force-sampled spans still pass through scrubbing

Do not claim broad PII protection without signal-specific evidence.

## Diagnostics and Health

Diagnostics should expose bounded live state, such as:

- tracing active/no-op
- agent/runtime mode
- active adapters
- sampling mode
- mutation gate state
- applied policy version/status
- scrubbing rule summary
- exporter/processor readiness
- actionable warnings

Do not expose:

- secrets
- PII
- raw payloads
- mutable live collections
- full environment
- implementation object dumps
- unbounded maps

Distinguish desired startup configuration from current applied runtime state.

Do not make liveness depend on optional collector/exporter availability.

## Runtime Control Observability

For control operations, make it possible to determine:

- operation
- structural decode result
- domain validation result
- mutation-policy result
- apply/read result
- state changed or unchanged
- active state version
- bounded reason code

Do not log raw control payloads.

Rejected operations must not change state.

## Exporter and Collector

Export must not block application request or reactive threads.

Use:

- bounded queues
- bounded retries
- asynchronous export
- explicit drop policy
- observable failures and queue pressure

Avoid:

- synchronous export
- unbounded queues/retries
- silent drops
- startup network calls from ordinary auto-configuration
- credential logging

One layer should own retry policy to avoid retry multiplication.

## No-Op and Disabled Behavior

Disabled/no-op mode must:

- preserve public API safety
- avoid network calls
- avoid state mutation
- avoid false export diagnostics
- remain independently tested
- avoid unnecessary allocation where practical
- preserve lifecycle and validation semantics that callers rely on

## Performance and Volume

For new high-volume telemetry, estimate:

- signals per request/message
- attributes/events/links per span
- metric series cardinality
- logs per failure loop
- exporter queue impact
- force-sampling amplification

Avoid:

- repeated regex compilation
- per-span temporary collections where unnecessary
- eager string formatting
- unbounded warning caches
- global synchronization
- reflection in hot paths

Correctness and privacy have priority over micro-optimization.

## Testing

Use layered verification:

- unit tests for policy, mapping, and invariants
- Spring tests for conditions/properties/diagnostics
- architecture tests for ownership and public surface
- integration/E2E for real propagation, export, sampling, scrubbing, JMX, agent, servlet, and WebFlux behavior

A test that only checks “some span exists” is insufficient when relationships, attributes, sampling, or duplicates matter.

A skipped required E2E is `INSUFFICIENT_EVIDENCE`, not `PASS`.

## Architecture Fitness

Protect where practical:

- no OTel SDK implementation types in public API
- no JMX/OpenMBean types in public API
- no custom W3C parser when official implementation is required
- no duplicate instrumentation path
- no runtime mutation enabled by default
- no unvalidated control payload apply
- no unsafe labels/attributes where statically detectable
- no legacy tracing symbols or packages
- servlet/WebFlux isolation

Do not weaken observability architecture gates to make generated code compile.

## Pre-Production Policy

Breaking observability changes are allowed when they materially improve:

- span semantics
- naming/cardinality
- privacy
- duplicate suppression
- runtime safety
- diagnostics
- architecture ownership
- performance

Prefer direct migration and deletion of obsolete telemetry paths over compatibility aliases or dual emission.

Do not use pre-production status to justify arbitrary telemetry churn.

## Verification and Report

Run the narrowest affected tests first, then architecture, build, and E2E gates required by the changed boundary.

A final report must include:

```text
Operational question:
Signals changed:
Owner module:
Names and dimensions:
Cardinality budget:
Sensitive-data assessment:
Sampling/scrubbing behavior:
Disabled/no-op behavior:
Failure/degradation:
Tests and E2E:
Architecture fitness:
Performance/volume impact:
Residual risks:
```

Use `PASS`, `PASS_WITH_WARNINGS`, `INSUFFICIENT_EVIDENCE`, or `FAIL` based on executed evidence.
